---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '../../components/Breadcrumb.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="LinkedIn OSINT Challenge - Sara's OSINT Resources">
  <article class="surface prose prose-invert max-w-none p-6 sm:p-10">
    <Breadcrumb
      items={[
        { label: 'Challenges', href: '/sara.osint/challenges' },
        { label: 'LinkedIn OSINT Challenge' },
      ]}
    />

    <PageHeader title="LinkedIn OSINT Challenge" />

    <div class="space-y-8 leading-relaxed">
      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">Step 1: Save the Original Image</h2>
        <p>Save original image.</p>
        <img
          src="/sara.osint/images/challenges/linkedin-step1-original.webp"
          alt="Original challenge photo showing a pier at night with white railings and stairs"
          loading="lazy"
          class="my-4 rounded-lg"
        />
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">Step 2: Note Any Artifacts</h2>
        <p>Note any artifacts in the image that could help identify the location.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">Step 3: Reverse Image Search</h2>
        <p>Reverse search with the search engine of your choice. I used Google.</p>
        <p class="mt-2">Other options:</p>
        <ul class="mt-2 list-disc space-y-1 pl-6">
          <li>
            <a href="https://yandex.com/images/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
              >Yandex Images</a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="https://lens.google.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
              >Google Lens</a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="https://tineye.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">TinEye</a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="https://www.bing.com/visualsearch" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
              >Bing Visual Search</a>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <img
          src="/sara.osint/images/challenges/linkedin-step3-reverse-search.webp"
          alt="Google reverse image search results for the pier photo"
          loading="lazy"
          class="my-4 rounded-lg"
        />
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">Step 4: Cropping and Refining</h2>
        <p>
          I altered the image portion size attempting to highlight the stairs or a combination of
          the lights and the distinct white railings. Cropping certain areas produces different
          results.
        </p>
        <img
          src="/sara.osint/images/challenges/linkedin-step4-cropped.webp"
          alt="Cropped image highlighting stairs and white railings for refined search"
          loading="lazy"
          class="my-4 rounded-lg"
        />
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">Step 5: Identifying Key Artifacts</h2>
        <p>
          Focusing on original or unique artifacts may help quicken the verification process in your
          search instead of the big picture.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-2">These caught my eye:</p>
        <ol class="mt-2 list-decimal space-y-1 pl-6">
          <li>The stairs separating the dock/pier area</li>
          <li>White railings</li>
          <li>Unique lighting</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="mt-4">
          I tested out the "white railing and pier dock" observances within a search:
        </p>
        <img
          src="/sara.osint/images/challenges/linkedin-step5-railing-search.webp"
          alt="Search results for white railings near piers and docks"
          loading="lazy"
          class="my-4 rounded-lg"
        />
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">Step 6: Scrolling Through Results</h2>
        <p>
          To my surprise I was overwhelmed with white railings near piers/docks or various
          combinations! Let's speed scroll, not too fast, though! I mentally noted the appearance of
          both stairs and railings in hopes of discovery.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 font-semibold">DO YOU SEE WHAT I SEE?</p>
        <img
          src="/sara.osint/images/challenges/linkedin-step6-results-match.webp"
          alt="Image search results showing a potential match among pier photos"
          loading="lazy"
          class="my-4 rounded-lg"
        />
        <p class="mt-4">Let's take a closer look!</p>
        <img
          src="/sara.osint/images/challenges/linkedin-step6-closer-look.webp"
          alt="Closer look at a matching pier photo showing similar railings and stairs"
          loading="lazy"
          class="my-4 rounded-lg"
        />
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">Step 7: Verifying the Location</h2>
        <p>
          The photo's description notes its location is: Cromer North Sea Norfolk East Anglia
          England UK. I input the location into Google Maps to further compare the night photograph
          and maps views.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Nope, the railings are facing the water and not the road like in the original. Not quite
          it, let's investigate further...
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">Step 8: Stock Photo Sites to the Rescue</h2>
        <p>
          I found
          <a
            href="https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo/pier-with-white-railings.html?sortBy=relevant"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer">www.alamy.com</a
          >
          and
          <a
            href="https://www.istockphoto.com/search/2/image?family=creative&phrase=blackpooll"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer">istockphoto.com</a
          >
          very useful!
        </p>
        <p class="mt-2">I led the search with "pier with white railings".</p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          I FOUND THE SHAPE! Now, the photo is in black and white -- I wanted to see if the railings
          were actually white -- seems so, let's continue!
        </p>
        <img
          src="/sara.osint/images/challenges/linkedin-step8-alamy-match.webp"
          alt="Alamy stock photo result showing matching pier shape with white railings - identified as Blackpool"
          loading="lazy"
          class="my-4 rounded-lg"
        />
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">Step 9: Blackpool Pier Confirmed</h2>
        <p>
          I took the location listed: BLACKPOOL PIER and put it through
          <a href="https://maps.google.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >Google Maps</a
          >.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-2 font-semibold">There are THREE piers in Blackpool!</p>
        <img
          src="/sara.osint/images/challenges/linkedin-step9-blackpool-map.webp"
          alt="Google Maps showing three piers in Blackpool"
          loading="lazy"
          class="my-4 rounded-lg"
        />
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
